node.text:
I’ve probably done about a hundred dives around Cocos Island in Costa Rica in search of those few, fleeting seconds where, hiding in the rocks underwater, you are fully immersed in the magic of one of Mother Nature’s awe-inspiring scenes. With a fair amount of patience and good fortune, you might find yourself underneath a school of scalloped hammerhead sharks floating effortlessly in the current above, gliding between the region’s many natural laboratories.

Enormous aggregations of endangered animals like hammerhead sharks, tiger sharks, sea turtles, and whales swim in the waters off the island 300 miles from the mainland. The region is up against industrial fishing, habitat destruction, pollution, climate change and, like the rest of the Eastern Tropical Pacific, it urgently needs more protection. 

I am hopeful that Costa Rica, along with its neighbors Ecuador and Colombia, will follow Panama's recent example of committing to protect 30 percent of its water by 2030. 

Visit only.one/etps (link in bio) to join the campaign with @sealegacy and @onlyone to close the gaps in protection and create the world’s first network of marine protected areas. 

#ETPSeascape #CostaRica #CocosIsland #MPA #30x30 #marinelife

node.text: Music is a universal language that can take an emotion and ground it. I love mixing the arts of music and motion! In a quick turnaround for the @j_corden @latelateshow - @leifvollebekk and I shot and edited this in a day for his recent appearance on the show. Shot on the @sonyalpha #a1 with a set of old, rehoused Leica - R primes that just create the vibe on their own. Thanks to the band @gregoryalanisakov @johnpaulgrigsby @rachelsliker and engineer @aberlinmusic @theblastingroom & @julienajarry for the camera builds, @ladzinski for the lighting and @davis_burch_ for AC. #SonyArtisan

node.text: I enjoy sharing the many colorful sides of our team, off working 100+ days at sea every year. It’s one big family out there @sealegacy. We are storytellers and conservationists but we are also fathers, mothers, students, and much more. Our tools are @sonyalpha cameras from which we strive to give a voice and a platform to those without: Sharing stories that inspire us, stories that drive us to take action, inform us, make us laugh and make us cry. All in the belief that shining a light where it’s needed most will have a positive impact in the world. // Video - Behind the scenes in Timor-Leste, invited to help create visual assets needed to educate, inform and campaign the for the greater protection of one of the world’s most biodiverse marine ecosystems. With @paulnicklen @mitty @samkretch @ryantidman @kyle.roepke @compassdiving @fizzybythesea @timorfixer #shotonsony #sonyalpha

Proud of this one.

node.text:
The Galápagos is a refuge for approximately 3,000 marine species, but despite pledges by the Ecuadorian government to protect this truly magical and biodiverse place, they have failed to do so. Industrial and unsustainable fishing practices are plundering its waters, devastating this delicate ecosystem. 

This is why I am calling on Ecuadorian President Lenín Moreno @leninmorenog and President of the National Assembly @cesarlitardo to fulfill their commitment to protect Galápagos and urgently expand the Galápagos Marine Reserve.

I believe there has never been a more critical, or more hopeful, time to act. Please show your support by signing the petition at only.one/galapagos or using the link in my bio. Then share it with your friends, family, and loved ones to help get them involved, too. Thank you for your support!

#masgalapagos #yoestoycongalapagos #galapagos #ecuador

node.text:
We often hear that the ocean is in trouble, so it may surprise you to learn that the ocean is one of our greatest allies in the race to address the catastrophic effects of the climate crisis.

The green trees and grasses that grow in the ocean can store up to 10 times more carbon than trees on land. The ocean, its coastal regions, and economic activities can provide extraordinary solutions with the potential to reduce our greenhouse gas emissions by nearly 4 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide per year in 2030. That’s equivalent to taking 2.5 billion cars off the road each year.

In the #GreenSeas Journey on @OnlyOne, we are discovering a new hope, and meeting the communities around the world who are working to protect, plant and reforest the ocean, the seas and coasts, making them green again. 💚 Visit the link in my bio to join us on this journey to unlock the power of the ocean as a climate solution. #OnlyOneOcean

node.text: Why is all this gear splayed out on a messy hotel bed? Well, my friends @zodiacwatches asked me to share my most essential gear. So, we're about to get into that. Waaaay into that. Actually don’t get into that. It’s a 35 minute, unscripted and unflattering unpacking of the 350 pounds of gear I’m taking to Cocos Island for @sealegacy. Solo documentary filmmaking gets quirky when you go underwater and then above water and then back underwater, three times a day...and you're the photographer. Drink everytime I say "um." // FYI: The watch I'm wearing is the impossible to find, out-of-stock, watermelon edition Super Sea Wolf. Or is it coming back in stock next month...hmmm ;-)

node.text: Today, the ocean is in trouble, and so are we. But it's not too late to chart a new course for the blue heart of this planet. The science says that if we protect 30% of the ocean by 2030, the ocean can rebound and continue to provide for us, the planet, and future generations. This is the core mission of the new #30x30 journey on @OnlyOne. I hope you'll take a moment to visit the platform to learn more and explore the new series within this journey featuring stories from our expeditions to Antarctica and Timor-Leste. Dive in at only.one/30x30 (link in bio). #OnlyOneOcean

node.text:
The @OnlyOne platform is finally live! Excited to share what we’ve been working on for years with the best team in the world. From our expeditions to Antarctica, Timor-Leste, and Cuba to opportunities to support marine protection, mangrove restoration, and other ocean projects, I hope you'll take a moment to explore the many powerful stories, solutions, and community action across the platform. Our road to recovery, knowledge, power, and change is within our reach. If we do it together. 💙
This platform belongs to everyone. Humbled to see it finally come to life. Please join the journey to protect the ocean, tackle the climate crisis, and help build a more just, equitable planet ➡️ only.one (link in bio) #OnlyOneOcean #TurningTheTide

node.text: Desert sunsets are an attack on the senses. I “feel” far more than I “see”within an image like this, captured on the #Xperia1iii. Beneath an explosion of color and light are the scents of juniper and pinyon. They ride on cool,  damp breezes that push away sun-scorched air and awaken my soul. It’s a fleeting moment of perfection. Happens everyday. @SonyXperia @SonyXperiaUS #SonyXperia #TravelByXperia #Mobilephotography #TakenWithXperia

Warning - graphic content. If this video breaks your heart too, sign the petition at the link in our bio to stop the killing of sharks in Costa Rica. ⁠
⁠
Costa Rica has more than 40 species of sharks, and almost half are in serious danger of extinction, including silky sharks and hammerhead sharks. Costa Rica, a country that prides itself on protecting its endangered marine wildlife, is doing an abysmal job of stemming the alarming decline of endangered shark species in its waters.⁠ 
⁠
Earlier this year, Costa Rica’s government essentially legalized the overfishing, and subsequent extinction, of endangered sharks. President @carlosalvq removed the ability of the Ministry of Environment to protect sharks, and shifted management responsibilities to the Institute of Fisheries and Aquaculture (INCOPESCA) – meaning they are no longer protected by Costa Rica’s Wildlife Conservation Law.⁠ Sign the petition at the link in my bio and share this post to help spread the word. Today, we are asking President Alvarado to immediately repeal his harmful executive decree and restore the Ministry of Environment’s authority to conserve and protect sharks. 
⁠
Video by @Shawnheinrichs,  @Andy_Mann⁠, and @paulnicklen - Conservation leadership by @randall_arauz @carola_ramirezcr @migramarnet @finsattached 
⁠

I’ve probably done about a hundred dives around Cocos Island in Costa Rica in search of those few, fleeting seconds where, hiding in the rocks underwater, you are fully immersed in the magic of one of Mother Nature’s awe-inspiring scenes. With a fair amount of patience and good fortune, you might find yourself underneath a school of scalloped hammerhead sharks floating effortlessly in the current above, gliding between the region’s many natural laboratories.

Enormous aggregations of endangered animals like hammerhead sharks, tiger sharks, sea turtles, and whales swim in the waters off the island 300 miles from the mainland. The region is up against industrial fishing, habitat destruction, pollution, climate change and, like the rest of the Eastern Tropical Pacific, it urgently needs more protection. 

I am hopeful that Costa Rica, along with its neighbors Ecuador and Colombia, will follow Panama's recent example of committing to protect 30 percent of its water by 2030. 

Visit only.one/etps (link in bio) to join the campaign with @sealegacy and @onlyone to close the gaps in protection and create the world’s first network of marine protected areas.
